      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix: harden package URL downloads",
        "body": "## Summary\n- Harden `source=url` package candidate downloads so release tooling rejects unsafe package URLs before fetching.\n- Add HTTPS-only, no-credentials, default-port validation plus private/internal/special-use hostname, literal IP, and DNS-result blocking.\n- Follow redirects manually and re-validate each target; bound downloads with timeout and max size; write to `target.tmp` and rename only after a complete download.\n- Add tooling tests for rejected unsafe URLs, redirect-to-metadata blocking, oversize cleanup, and successful atomic writes.\n\n## Test Plan\n- [x] `OPENCLAW_VITEST_MAX_WORKERS=1 node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run --config test/vitest/vitest.tooling.config.ts test/scripts/resolve-openclaw-package-candidate.test.ts`\n- [x] `pnpm lint`\n- [x] `pnpm build`\n- [x] `pnpm test:changed:max`\n- [x] `pnpm check:test-types`\n- [x] `git diff --check`\n- [x] Added-line static scan for hardcoded secrets and dangerous eval/shell/deserialization/SQL patterns: 0 matches\n\n## Real behavior proof\n- Behavior or issue addressed: `scripts/resolve-openclaw-package-candidate.mjs --source url` previously streamed any HTTPS URL directly. This patch makes the real download helper reject private/internal targets, validate redirects, enforce byte limits, and leave no partial target or temp file after failed oversized downloads.\n- Real environment tested: Local OpenClaw checkout `/home/rev/projects/openclaw` on branch `fix/package-url-download-hardening`, commit `6bbdc086243a8da204d89b4f3e2b2e6ffdff3146`, using Node from the repository environment.\n- Exact steps or command run after the patch:\n  ```bash\n  cd /home/rev/projects/openclaw\n  node /tmp/openclaw-package-url-proof-6c7917518f.mjs\n  ```\n- Evidence after fix: Terminal capture from the direct Node runtime proof script that imports the patched `downloadUrl` production helper and exercises rejected localhost, rejected private DNS resolution, rejected redirect to the cloud metadata IP, oversize cleanup, and successful atomic write:\n  ```json\n  {\n    \"blocked\": {\n      \"localhost\": true,\n      \"privateDns\": true,\n      \"redirectToMetadata\": true\n    },\n    \"requestedUrls\": [\n      \"https://packages.example/openclaw.tgz\"\n    ],\n    \"atomic\": {\n      \"oversizeRejected\": true,\n      \"targetMissingAfterOversize\": true,\n      \"tmpMissingAfterOversize\": true,\n      \"finalBytes\": [\n        1,\n        2,\n        3\n      ],\n      \"tmpMissingAfterSuccess\": true\n    }\n  }\n  ```\n- Observed result after fix: The production helper rejected all unsafe URL/redirect cases before fetching private targets, rejected an oversized response, removed the temp file after failure, and wrote the expected final bytes only after a successful bounded download.\n- What was not tested: A live public internet tarball download from GitHub Actions; the direct runtime proof used deterministic `fetchImpl`/DNS hooks to exercise the real helper without contacting external or private networks. The existing SHA-256 tarball verification path was left unchanged and remains covered by the existing package candidate flow tests.\n",
        "branch": "fix/package-url-download-hardening",
